Midgaard's Three Civic Oaths are the foundational commitments sworn by wardens, administrators, and charter-holding officials at appointment and renewal.
The First Oath is the Oath of Stone: "No judgment hidden, no sentence unrecorded" — requiring that all official decisions be documented in accessible registries.
The Second Oath is the Oath of Light: "No ward unlit, no traveler uncounted" — requiring that civic infrastructure be maintained and that passage through civic space be witnessed.
The Third Oath is the Oath of Bread: "No levy taken that cannot be borne" — requiring that all civic exactions be calibrated against the capacity of those who bear them.
Together the three oaths define Midgaard's civic ethics: transparency in judgment, continuity of service, proportionality in burden.
All three are invoked at the Bell Watch — the fifth of Midgaard's seven watches — when official notices are read aloud and contracts are closed for the day.
The oaths are sworn on the Oath Stone in the Magistrate Ledgerhouse's public chamber, a practice older than the Violet Compact.
The Continuity faction interprets the oaths as procedures: compliance is demonstrated through correct process.
The Reckoning faction interprets the oaths as standards: compliance is demonstrated through outcomes, and the Unindexed Years show all three oaths were violated.
The Last Burden Tithe was explicitly contested under the Third Oath's "cannot be borne" provision; officials argued the Oath applied to living levies, not funerary ones.
The oaths are recited publicly at each warden appointment; they are the ritual anchor of road administration legitimacy.

