---
Ushabti judicial analysts evaluate the Three Civic Oaths as a distributed claim system: each oath is a claim made by the institution, evidence of compliance is measurable, and verdict on compliance is assessable. The Oath of Stone is the most amenable to Ushabti analysis: documentation records are either present or absent, and the evidentiary standard is clear. The Oath of Bread is the most contested: "cannot be borne" is a threshold claim requiring a measurement standard that Midgaard has never formally defined. The Three Oaths together constitute an institutional self-binding mechanism that Ushabti regard as structurally sound but operationally ambiguous — the commitments are clear, the compliance standards are not.

